A server hold the "source of truth" for the value of `{{prop_name}}`.  An `Arc` pointer can be copied and moved that points to the server's property value.   Here is how to write a new value:

```rust
let {{prop_name|snake_case}}_handle = server.get_{{prop_name|snake_case}}_handle();
{
    let mut {{prop_name|snake_case}}_guard = {{prop_name|snake_case}}_handle.write().await;
    {%-if prop.arg_list | length == 1 %}
    *{{prop_name|snake_case}}_guard = {{prop.arg_list[0].get_random_example_value(lang="rust", seed=4)}};
    {%else%}
    let new_{{prop_name|snake_case}}_value = {{prop.rust_type}} {
        {%-for arg in prop.arg_list %}
            {{arg.name|snake_case}}: {{arg.get_random_example_value(lang="rust", seed=4)}},
        {%-endfor%}
    };
    *{{prop_name|snake_case}}_guard = new_{{prop_name|snake_case}}_value;
    {%endif-%}

    // Optional, block until the property is published to the MQTT broker:
    {{prop_name|snake_case}}_guard.commit(std::time::Duration::from_secs(2)).await;

    // If not committed, the property will be published when the guard is dropped in "fire-and-forget" mode.
}

```

If only reading the value, a read guard can be used:

```rust
